# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buddhist-vegetarianism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The **14th Dalai Lama** (born **Lhamo Thondup**; 6 July 1935; full spiritual name: **Jetsun Jamphel Ngawang Lobsang Yeshe Tenzin Gyatso**, shortened as **Tenzin Gyatso**) is the incumbent Dalai Lama, the highest spiritual leader and head of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He served as the resident spiritual and temporal leader of Tibet before 1959, and subsequently led the Tibetan government in exile represented by the Central Tibetan Administration in Dharamshala, India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] A belief central to the Tibetan Buddhist tradition as well as the institution of the Dalai Lama is that the reincarnated person is a living Bodhisattva, specifically an emanation of Avalokiteśvara (in Sanskrit) or Chenrezig (in Tibetan), the Bodhisattva of Compassion.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Mongolic word *dalai* means *ocean.* The 14th Dalai Lama is also known to Tibetans as **Gyalwa Rinpoche** ("The Precious Jewel-like Buddha-Master"), *Kundun* ("The Presence"), and *Yizhin Norbu* ("The Wish-Fulfilling Gem").
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His devotees, as well as much of the Western world, often call him ***His Holiness the Dalai Lama***.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He is the leader and a monk of the newest Gelug school of Tibetan Buddhism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama was born to a farming family in Taktser (*Hongya* village), in the traditional Tibetan region of Amdo, at the time a Chinese frontier district.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was selected as the tulku of the 13th Dalai Lama in 1937, and formally recognised as the 14th Dalai Lama in 1939.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As with the recognition process for his predecessor, a Golden Urn selection process was waived and approved by the Nationalist government of China.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His enthronement ceremony was held in Lhasa on 22 February 1940.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following the Battle of Chamdo, in which PRC forces annexed Central Tibet, the Tibetan government, the Ganden Phodrang, invested the Dalai Lama with temporal duties on 17 November 1950 (at 15 years of age), which he held until his exile in 1959.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] During the 1959 Tibetan uprising, the Dalai Lama escaped to India, where he continues to live.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 29 April 1959, the Dalai Lama established the independent Tibetan government in exile in the north Indian hill station of Mussoorie, which then moved in May 1960 to Dharamshala, where he resides.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He retired as political head in 2011 to make way for a democratic government, the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama advocates for the welfare of Tibetans and since the early 1970s has called for the Middle Way Approach with China to peacefully resolve the issue of Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He criticised the CIA Tibetan program, saying that its sudden end in 1972 proved it was primarily aimed at serving American interests.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Up until his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama travelled worldwide to give Tibetan Mahayana and Vajrayana Buddhism teachings, and his Kalachakra teachings and initiations were international events.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He also attended conferences on a wide range of subjects, including the relationship between religion and science, met with other world leaders, religious leaders, philosophers, and scientists, online and in-person.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Since 2018, he has continued to teach on a reduced schedule, limiting his travel to within India only, and occasionally addressing international audiences via live webcasts.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His work includes focus on the environment, economics, women's rights, nonviolence, interfaith dialogue, physics, astronomy, Buddhism and science, cognitive neuroscience, reproductive health and sexuality.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1989.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] *Time* magazine named the Dalai Lama Gandhi's spiritual heir to nonviolence.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In addition, an Indian MP delegation led by Sujeet Kumar, Member of Parliament, Rajya Sabha has advocated for the Dalai Lama to receive the Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour in India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Lhamo Thondup was born on 6 July 1935, to Choekyong Tsering and his wife Dekyi Tsering, a farming and horse trading family in the small hamlet of Taktser under the control of the Ma clique loyal to the Republic of China as part of Qinghai and on the edge of the traditionally Tibetan region of Amdo.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He was one of seven siblings to survive childhood and one of the three supposed reincarnated Rinpoches in the same family.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest sister, Tsering Dolma, was 16 years his senior and was midwife to his mother at his birth.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] She would accompany him into exile and found Tibetan Children's Villages.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His eldest brother, Thupten Jigme Norbu, had been recognised at the age of three by the 13th Dalai Lama as the reincarnation of the high Lama, the 6th Taktser Rinpoche.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His fifth brother, Tendzin Choegyal, had been recognised as the 16th Ngari Rinpoche.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] His sister, Jetsun Pema, spent most of her adult life on the Tibetan Children's Villages project.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Dalai Lama has said that his first language was "a broken Xining language which was (a dialect of) the Chinese language, a form of Central Plains Mandarin", and his family speaks neither Amdo Tibetan nor Lhasa Tibetan.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] After the demise of the 13th Dalai Lama, in 1935, the Ordinance of Lama Temple Management was published by the Central Government.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1936, the Method of Reincarnation of Lamas was published by the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission of the Central Government.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 3 states that death of lamas, including the Dalai Lama and Panchen Lama, should be reported to the commission, soul boys should be located and checked by the commission, and a lot-drawing ceremony with the Golden Urn system should be held.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 6 states that local governments should invite officials from the Central Government to take care of the sitting-in-the-bed ceremony.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Article 7 states that soul boys should not be sought from current lama families.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This article echoes what the Qianlong Emperor described in The Discourse of Lama to eliminate greedy families with multiple reincarnated rinpoches, lamas.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Based on custom and regulation, the regent was actively involved in the search for the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Following reported signs and visions, three search teams were sent out to the north-east, the east, and the south-east to locate the new incarnation when the boy who was to become the 14th Dalai Lama was about two years old.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Sir Basil Gould, British delegate to Lhasa in 1936, related his account of the north-eastern team to Sir Charles Alfred Bell, former British resident in Lhasa and friend of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Among other omens, the head of the embalmed body of the 13th Dalai Lama, at first facing south-east, had turned to face the north-east, indicating, it was interpreted, the direction in which his successor would be found.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Regent, Reting Rinpoche, shortly afterwards had a vision at the sacred lake of Lhamo La-tso which he interpreted as Amdo being the region to search.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] This vision was also interpreted to refer to a large monastery with a gilded roof and turquoise tiles, and a twisting path from there to a hill to the east, opposite which stood a small house with distinctive eaves.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The team, led by Kewtsang Rinpoche, went first to meet the Panchen Lama, who had been stuck in Jyekundo, in northern Kham.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The Panchen Lama had been investigating births of unusual children in the area ever since the death of the 13th Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He gave Kewtsang the names of three boys whom he had discovered and identified as candidates.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Within a year the Panchen Lama had died.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two of his three candidates were crossed off the list but the third, a "fearless" child, the most promising, was from Taktser village, which, as in the vision, was on a hill, at the end of a trail leading to Taktser from the great Kumbum Monastery with its gilded, turquoise roof.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] There they found a house, as interpreted from the vision—the house where Lhamo Dhondup lived.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 14th Dalai Lama claims that at the time, the village of Taktser stood right on the "real border" between the region of Amdo and China.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the search lore, when the team visited, posing as pilgrims, its leader, a Sera Lama, pretended to be the servant and sat separately in the kitchen.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He held an old mala that had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama, and the boy Lhamo Dhondup, aged two, approached and asked for it.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The monk said, "If you know who I am, you can have it." The child said, "Sera Lama, Sera Lama", and spoke with him in a Lhasa accent, in a dialect the boy's mother could not understand.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The next time the party returned to the house, they revealed their real purpose and asked permission to subject the boy to certain tests.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] One test consisted of showing him various pairs of objects, one of which had belonged to the 13th Dalai Lama and one which had not.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In every case, he chose the Dalai Lama's own objects and rejected the others.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] From 1936 the Hui "Ma clique" Muslim warlord Ma Bufang ruled Qinghai as its governor under the nominal authority of the Republic of China central government.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to an interview with the 14th Dalai Lama, in the 1930s, Ma Bufang had seized this north-east corner of Amdo in the name of Chiang Kai-shek's weak government and incorporated it into the Chinese province of Qinghai.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Before going to Taktser, Kewtsang had gone to Ma Bufang to pay his respects.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] When Ma Bufang heard a candidate had been found in Taktser, he had the family brought to him in Xining.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He first demanded proof that the boy was the Dalai Lama, but the Lhasa government, though informed by Kewtsang that this was the one, told Kewtsang to say he had to go to Lhasa for further tests with other candidates.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They knew that if he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, the Chinese government would insist on sending a large army escort with him, which would then stay in Lhasa and refuse to budge.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Ma Bufang, together with Kumbum Monastery, then refused to allow him to depart unless he was declared to be the Dalai Lama, but withdrew this demand in return for 100,000 Chinese dollars ransom in silver to be shared among them, to let them go to Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Two years of diplomatic wrangling followed before it was accepted by Lhasa that the ransom had to be paid to avoid the Chinese getting involved and escorting him to Lhasa with a large army.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Meanwhile, the boy was kept at Kumbum where two of his brothers were already studying as monks and recognised incarnate lamas.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The payment of 300,000 silver dollars was then advanced by Muslim traders en route to Mecca in a large caravan via Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] They paid Ma Bufang on behalf of the Tibetan government against promissory notes to be redeemed, with interest, in Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The 20,000-dollar fee for an escort was dropped, since the Muslim merchants invited them to join their caravan for protection; Ma Bufang sent 20 of his soldiers with them and was paid from both sides since the Chinese government granted him another 50,000 dollars for the expenses of the journey.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Furthermore, the Indian government helped the Tibetans raise the ransom funds by affording them import concessions.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 22 September 1938, representatives of Tibet Office in Beijing informed Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that 3 candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held in Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In October 1938, the Method of Using Golden Urn for the 14th Dalai Lama was drafted by Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] On 12 December 1938, regent Jamphel Yeshe Gyaltsen, the serving Reting Rinpoche, informed the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission that three candidates were found and ceremony of Golden Urn would be held.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] Released from Kumbum, on 21 July 1939 the party travelled across Tibet on a journey to Lhasa in the large Muslim caravan with Lhamo Dhondup, now four years old, riding with his brother Lobsang in a special palanquin carried by two mules, two years after being discovered.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] As soon as they were out of Ma Bufang's area, he was officially declared to be the 14th Dalai Lama by the Kashag, and after ten weeks of travel he arrived in Lhasa on 8 October 1939.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The ordination (pabbajja) and giving of the monastic name of Tenzin Gyatso were arranged by Reting Rinpoche and according to the Dalai Lama "I received my ordination from Kyabjé Ling Rinpoché in the Jokhang in Lhasa." There was very limited Chinese involvement at this time.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The family of the 14th Dalai Lama was elevated to the highest stratum of the Tibetan aristocracy and acquired land and serf holdings, as with the families of previous Dalai Lamas.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] In 1959, at the age of 23, he took his final examination at Lhasa's Jokhang Temple during the annual Monlam Prayer Festival.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] He passed with honours and was awarded the Lharampa degree, the highest-level *geshe* degree, roughly equivalent to a doctorate in Buddhist philosophy.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] According to the Dalai Lama, he had a succession of tutors in Tibet including Reting Rinpoche, Tathag Rinpoche, Ling Rinpoche and lastly Trijang Rinpoche, who became junior tutor when he was 19.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] At the age of 11 he met the Austrian mountaineer Heinrich Harrer, who became his videographer and tutor about the world outside Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p01] The two remained friends until Harrer's death in 2006.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Historically the Dalai Lamas or their regents held political and religious leadership over Tibet from Lhasa with varying degrees of influence depending on the regions of Tibet and periods of history.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This began with the 5th Dalai Lama's rule in 1642 and lasted until the 1950s (except for 1705–1750), during which period the Dalai Lamas headed the Tibetan government or Ganden Phodrang.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until 1912 however, when the 13th Dalai Lama declared the complete independence of Tibet, their rule was generally subject to patronage and protection of firstly Mongol kings (1642–1720) and then the Manchu-led Qing dynasty (1720–1912).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterwards in 1939, at the age of four, the Dalai Lama was taken in a procession of lamas to Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Former British officials stationed in India and Tibet recalled that envoys from Britain and China were present at the Dalai Lama's enthronement in February 1940.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] According to Basil Gould, the Chinese representative Wu Chunghsin was reportedly unhappy about the position he had during the ceremony.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Afterward an article appeared in the Chinese press falsely claiming that Wu personally announced the installation of the Dalai Lama, who supposedly prostrated himself to Wu in gratitude.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After his enthronement, the Dalai Lama's childhood was then spent between the Potala Palace and Norbulingka, his summer residence, both of which are now UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang Kai Shek ordered Ma Bufang to put his Muslim soldiers on alert for an invasion of Tibet in 1942.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang complied, and moved several thousand troops to the border with Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chiang also threatened the Tibetans with aerial bombardment if they worked with the Japanese.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Ma Bufang attacked the Tibetan Buddhist Tsang monastery in 1941.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He also constantly attacked the Labrang monastery.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 1950 the army of the People's Republic of China marched to the edge of the Dalai Lama's territory and sent a delegation after defeating a legion of the Tibetan army in warlord-controlled Kham.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 17 November 1950, at the age of 15, the 14th Dalai Lama assumed full temporal (political) power as ruler of Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's formal rule as head of the government in Tibet was brief although he was enthroned as spiritual leader on 22 February 1940.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When Chinese cadres entered Tibet in 1950, with a crisis looming, the Dalai Lama was asked to assume the role of head of state at the age of 15, which he did on 17 November 1950.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Customarily the Dalai Lama would typically assume control at about the age of 20.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He sent a delegation to Beijing, which signed the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama believes the draft agreement was written by China.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Tibetan representatives were not allowed to suggest any alterations and China did not allow the Tibetan representatives to communicate with the Tibetan government in Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan delegation was not authorised by Lhasa to sign, but ultimately submitted to pressure from the Chinese to sign anyway, using seals specifically made for the purpose.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Seventeen Point Agreement recognised Chinese sovereignty over Tibet, but China allowed the Dalai Lama to continue to rule Tibet internally, and it allowed the system of feudal peasantry to persist.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1951, following a lengthy discussion with the returning delegates, the National Assembly recommended that the Dalai Lama accept the Seventeen Point Agreement.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He telegraphed his confirmation to Chairman Mao Zedong on 24 October.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scholar Robert Barnett wrote of the serfdom controversy: "So even if it were agreed that serfdom and feudalism existed in Tibet, this would be little different other than in technicalities from conditions in any other 'premodern' peasant society, including most of China at that time.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The power of the Chinese argument therefore lies in its implication that serfdom, and with it feudalism, is inseparable from extreme abuse.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Evidence to support this linkage has not been found by scholars other than those close to Chinese governmental circles.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The 19-year-old Dalai Lama toured China for almost a year from 1954 to 1955, meeting many of the revolutionary leaders and the top echelon of the Chinese communist leadership who created modern China.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He learned Chinese and socialist ideals, as explained by his Chinese hosts, on a tour of China showcasing the benefits of socialism and the effective governance provided to turn the large, impoverished nation into a modern and egalitarian society, which impressed him.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In September 1954, he went to the Chinese capital to meet Chairman Mao Zedong with the 10th Panchen Lama and attend the 1st National People's Congress as a delegate, primarily discussing China's constitution.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On 27 September 1954, the Dalai Lama was selected as a Vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, a post he officially held until 1964.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1956, on a trip to India to celebrate the Buddha's Birthday, the Dalai Lama asked the Prime Minister of India, Jawaharlal Nehru, if he would allow him political asylum should he choose to stay.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Nehru discouraged this as a provocation against peace, and reminded him of the Indian Government's non-interventionist stance agreed upon with its 1954 treaty with China.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Long called a "splittist" and "traitor" by China, the Dalai Lama has attempted formal talks over Tibet's status in China.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Chinese Foreign Ministry has warned the US and other countries to "shun" the Dalai Lama during visits and often uses trade negotiations and human rights talks as an incentive to do so.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] China sporadically bans images of the Dalai Lama and arrests citizens for owning photos of him in Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In April 2018, the Dalai Lama confirmed Chinese government claims about Gedhun Choekyi Nyima by saying that he knew from "reliable sources" that the Panchen Lama he had recognised was alive and receiving normal education.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He said he hoped that the Chinese-recognised Panchen Lama (Gyaincain Norbu) studied well under the guidance of a good teacher, adding that there were instances in Tibetan Buddhist tradition, of a reincarnated lama taking more than one manifestation.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is a target of Chinese state sponsored hacking.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Security experts claim "targeting Tibetan activists is a strong indicator of official Chinese government involvement" since economic information is the primary goal of private Chinese hackers.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009 the personal office of the Dalai Lama asked researchers at the Munk Center for International Studies at the University of Toronto to check its computers for malicious software.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] A second cyberspy network, Shadow Network, was discovered by the same researchers in 2010.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Stolen documents included a year's worth of the Dalai Lama's personal email, and classified government material relating to India, West Africa, the Russian Federation, the Middle East, and NATO.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] "Sophisticated" hackers were linked to universities in China, Beijing again denied involvement.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Chinese hackers posing as The New York Times, Amnesty International and other organisation's reporters targeted the private office of the Dalai Lama, Tibetan Parliament members, and Tibetan nongovernmental organisations, among others, in 2019.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the outset of the 1959 Tibetan uprising, fearing for his life, the Dalai Lama and his retinue fled Tibet with the help of the CIA's Special Activities Division, crossing into India on 30 March 1959, reaching Tezpur in Assam on 18 April.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Some time later he set up the Government of Tibet in Exile in Dharamshala, India, which is often referred to as "*Little Lhasa*".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] After the founding of the government in exile he re-established the approximately 80,000 Tibetan refugees who followed him into exile in agricultural settlements.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He created a Tibetan educational system in order to teach the Tibetan children the language, history, religion, and culture.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Tibetan Institute of Performing Arts was established in 1959 and the Central Institute of Higher Tibetan Studies became the primary university for Tibetans in India in 1967.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He supported the refounding of 200 monasteries and nunneries in an attempt to preserve Tibetan Buddhist teachings and the Tibetan way of life.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama appealed to the United Nations on the rights of Tibetans.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This appeal resulted in three resolutions adopted by the General Assembly in 1959, 1961, and 1965, all before the People's Republic was allowed representation at the United Nations.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The resolutions called on China to respect the human rights of Tibetans.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1963, he promulgated a democratic constitution which is based upon the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, creating an elected parliament and an administration to champion his cause.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1970, he opened the Library of Tibetan Works and Archives in Dharamshala which houses over 80,000 manuscripts and important knowledge resources related to Tibetan history, politics and culture.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] It is considered one of the most important institutions for Tibetology in the world.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2016, there were demands from Indian citizens and politicians of different political parties to confer the Dalai Lama the prestigious Bharat Ratna, the highest civilian honour of India, which has only been awarded to a non-Indian citizen twice in its history.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2021, it was revealed that the Dalai Lama's inner circle were listed in the Pegasus project data as having been targeted with spyware on their phones.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Analysis strongly indicates potential targets were selected by the Indian government.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2025, Indian Members of Parliament (MPs), led by Sujeet Kumar, BJP Rajya Sabha MP, called for His Holiness to be awarded the Bharat Ratna.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] At the Congressional Human Rights Caucus in 1987 in Washington, D.C., the Dalai Lama gave a speech outlining his ideas for the future status of Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan called for Tibet to become a democratic "zone of peace" without nuclear weapons, and with support for human rights.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The plan would come to be known as the "Strasbourg proposal", because the Dalai Lama expanded on the plan at Strasbourg on 15 June 1988.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] There, he proposed the creation of a self-governing Tibet "in association with the People's Republic of China." This would have been pursued by negotiations with the PRC government, but the plan was rejected by the Tibetan Government-in-Exile in 1991.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has indicated that he wishes to return to Tibet only if the People's Republic of China agrees not to make any precondition for his return.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In the 1970s, the Paramount leader Deng Xiaoping set China's sole return requirement to the Dalai Lama as that he "must [come back] as a Chinese citizen ... that is, patriotism".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama celebrated his 70th birthday on 6 July 2005.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] About 10,000 Tibetan refugees, monks and foreign tourists gathered outside his home.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Patriarch Alexius II of the Russian Orthodox Church alleged positive relations with Buddhists.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] However, later that year, the Russian state prevented the Dalai Lama from fulfilling an invitation to the traditionally Buddhist republic of Kalmykia.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The President of the Republic of China (Taiwan), Chen Shui-bian, attended an evening celebrating the Dalai Lama's birthday at the Chiang Kai-shek Memorial Hall in Taipei.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In October 2008 in Japan, the Dalai Lama addressed the 2008 Tibetan violence that had erupted and that the Chinese government accused him of fomenting.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He responded that he had "lost faith" in efforts to negotiate with the Chinese government, and that it was "up to the Tibetan people" to decide what to do.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] During his visit to Taiwan after Typhoon Morakot 30 Taiwanese indigenous peoples protested against the Dalai Lama and denounced it as politically motivated.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is an advocate for a world free of nuclear weapons, and serves on the Advisory Council of the Nuclear Age Peace Foundation.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama has voiced his support for the Campaign for the Establishment of a United Nations Parliamentary Assembly, an organisation which campaigns for democratic reformation of the United Nations, and the creation of a more accountable international political system.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Until reaching his mid-80s, the Dalai Lama maintained a busy international lecture and teaching schedule.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, he has continued to teach, but has limited his travel to within India only.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] His public talks and teachings are usually webcast live in multiple languages, via an inviting organisation's website, or on the Dalai Lama's own website.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Scores of his past teaching videos can be viewed there, as well as public talks, conferences, interviews, dialogues and panel discussions.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's best known teaching subject is the Kalachakra tantra which, as of 2014, he had conferred a total of 33 times, most often in India's upper Himalayan regions but also in the Western world.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Kalachakra (Wheel of Time) is one of the most complex teachings of Buddhism, sometimes taking two weeks to confer, and he often confers it on very large audiences, up to 200,000 students and disciples at a time.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama is the author of numerous books on Buddhism, many of them on general Buddhist subjects but also including books on particular topics like Dzogchen, a Nyingma practice.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Since 2018, his schedule has contained fewer engagements, with most occurring in India along with a handful webcasts to international audiences.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Again in London in 1996 he taught the Four Noble Truths, the basis and foundation of Buddhism accepted by all Buddhists, at the combined invitation of 27 different Buddhist organisations of all schools and traditions belonging to the Network of Buddhist Organisations UK.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In India, no fees are charged to attend these teachings since costs are covered by requesting sponsors.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] When he travels abroad to give teachings there is usually a ticket fee calculated by the inviting organisation to cover the costs involved and any surplus is normally to be donated to recognised charities.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has frequently visited and lectured at colleges and universities, some of which have conferred honorary degrees upon him.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Dozens of videos of recorded webcasts of the Dalai Lama's public talks on general subjects for non-Buddhists like peace, happiness and compassion, modern ethics, the environment, economic and social issues, gender, the empowerment of women and so forth can be viewed in his office's archive.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama met Pope Paul VI at the Vatican in 1973.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1990, he met a delegation of Jewish teachers in Dharamshala for an extensive interfaith dialogue.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has since visited Israel three times, and in 2006 met the Chief Rabbi of Israel.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2006, he met Pope Benedict XVI privately.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has met the Archbishop of Canterbury, Dr.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Robert Runcie, and other leaders of the Anglican Church in London, Gordon B.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Hinckley, who at the time was the president of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, as well as senior Eastern Orthodox Church, Muslim, Hindu, Jewish, and Sikh officials.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1996 and 2002, he participated in the first two Gethsemani Encounters hosted by the Monastic Interreligious Dialogue at the Abbey of Our Lady of Gethsemani, where Thomas Merton, whom the Dalai Lama had met in the late 1960s, had lived.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He is also a member of the Board of World Religious Leaders as part of The Elijah Interfaith Institute and participated in the Third Meeting of the Board of World Religious Leaders in Amritsar, India, on 26 November 2007 to discuss the topic of Love and Forgiveness.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2009, the Dalai Lama inaugurated an interfaith "World Religions-Dialogue and Symphony" conference at Gujarat's Mahuva religions, according to Morari Bapu.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2010, the Dalai Lama, joined by a panel of scholars, launched the Common Ground Project, in Bloomington, Indiana (USA), which was planned by himself and Prince Ghazi bin Muhammad of Jordan during several years of personal conversations.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The project is based on the book *Common Ground between Islam and Buddhism*.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2019, the Dalai Lama fully sponsored the first-ever 'Celebrating Diversity in the Muslim World' conference in New Delhi on behalf of the Muslims of Ladakh.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama's lifelong interest in science and technology dates from his childhood in Lhasa, Tibet, when he was fascinated by mechanical objects like clocks, watches, telescopes, film projectors, clockwork soldiers and motor cars, and loved to repair, disassemble and reassemble them.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Once, observing the Moon through a telescope as a child, he realised it was a crater-pocked lump of rock and not a heavenly body emitting its own light as Tibetan cosmologists had taught him.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] He has also said that had he not been brought up as a monk he would probably have been an engineer.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On his first trip to the west in 1973 he asked to visit Cambridge University's astrophysics department in the UK and he sought out renowned scientists such as Sir Karl Popper, David Bohm and Carl Friedrich von Weizsäcker, who taught him the basics of science.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama sees important common ground between science and Buddhism in having the same approach to challenge dogma on the basis of empirical evidence that comes from observation and analysis of phenomena.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Also in 1983, the American social entrepreneur and innovator R.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Adam Engle, who had become aware of the Dalai Lama's deep interest in science, was already considering the idea of facilitating for him a serious dialogue with a selection of appropriate scientists.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 1984 Engle formally offered to the Dalai Lama's office to organise a week-long, formal dialogue for him with a suitable team of scientists, provided that the Dalai Lama would wish to fully participate in such a dialogue.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Within 48 hours the Dalai Lama confirmed to Engle that he was "truly interested in participating in something substantial about science" so Engle proceeded with launching the project.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Francisco Varela, having heard about Engle's proposal, then called him to tell him of his earlier discussions with the Dalai Lama and to offer his scientific collaboration to the project.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Engle accepted, and Varela assisted him to assemble his team of six specialist scientists for the first 'Mind and Life' dialogue on the cognitive sciences, which was eventually held with the Dalai Lama at his residence in Dharamsala in 1987.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This five-day event was so successful that at the end the Dalai Lama told Engle he would very much like to repeat it again in the future.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As Mind and Life Institute's remit expanded, Engle formalised the organisation as a non-profit foundation after the third dialogue, held in 1990, which initiated the undertaking of neurobiological research programmes in the United States under scientific conditions.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Sponsors and partners in these dialogues have included the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Johns Hopkins University, the Mayo Clinic, and Zurich University.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Apart from time spent teaching Buddhism and fulfilling responsibilities to his Tibetan followers, the Dalai Lama spends time and resources investigating the interface between Buddhism and science through the ongoing series of Mind and Life dialogues and its spin-offs.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] As the institute's Cofounder and the Honorary chairman he has personally presided over and participated in all its dialogues, which continue to expand worldwide.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have given rise to dozens of DVD sets of the dialogues and books he has authored on them such as *Ethics for the New Millennium* and *The Universe in a Single Atom*, as well as scientific papers and university research programmes.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] On the Tibetan and Buddhist side, science subjects have been added to the curriculum for Tibetan monastic educational institutions and scholarship.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] SEE learning focuses on developing critical thinking, ethical reasoning and compassion and stresses on commonalities rather than on the differences.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In particular, the Mind and Life Education Humanities & Social Sciences initiatives have been instrumental in developing the emerging field of Contemplative Science, by researching, for example, the effects of contemplative practice on the human brain, behaviour and biology.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] These activities have even had an impact in the Chinese capital.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2013 an 'academic dialogue' with a Chinese scientist, a Tibetan 'living Buddha' and a professor of Religion took place in Beijing.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] Entitled "High-end dialogue: ancient Buddhism and modern science" it addressed the same considerations that interest the Dalai Lama, described as 'discussing about the similarities between Buddhism and modern science'.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] The Dalai Lama uses various meditation techniques, including analytic meditation and emptiness meditation.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In 2007, the 14th Dalai Lama said his reincarnation could be a woman.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] This was mentioned again in 2015 and 2019.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p02] In May 2011, the Dalai Lama retired from the Central Tibetan Administration.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2011, the Dalai Lama repeated his statement in an interview with Canadian CTV News.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He added that Chinese laws banning the selection of successors based on reincarnation will not impact his decisions.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "Naturally my next life is entirely up to me.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And also this is not a political matter", he said in the interview.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama also added that he has not decided on whether he would reincarnate or be the last Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview with the German newspaper *Welt am Sonntag* published on 7 September 2014 the Dalai Lama stated "the institution of the Dalai Lama has served its purpose", and that "We had a Dalai Lama for almost five centuries.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The 14th Dalai Lama now is very popular.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Let us then finish with a popular Dalai Lama." In response, the Chinese government said the title of Dalai Lama has been conferred by the central government for hundreds of years and the 14th Dalai Lama has ulterior motives.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This was taken by Tibetan activists and *The Wire* to mean that China will make the Dalai Lama reincarnate no matter what.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Gyatso has also expressed fear that the Chinese government would manipulate any reincarnation selection in order to choose a successor that would go along with their political goals.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015, the 14th Dalai Lama has claimed he may be reincarnated as a mischievous blonde woman.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama said that if a female Dalai Lama comes, she should be more attractive.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Chinese politician Padma Choling accused the 14th Dalai Lama of flip-flopping with his various statements on the issue, and of hypocrisy as he himself was reincarnated.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also accused the 14th Dalai Lama of profaning Tibetan Buddhism "by doubting his reincarnation".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2019, the 14th Dalai Lama stated that because of the feudal origin of the Dalai Lama reincarnation system, the reincarnation system should end.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, in July 2025, as the 14th Dalai Lama reached the age of 90, he addressed growing discussions about his succession by reaffirming that he will be reincarnated and that the process of identifying his successor should follow traditional Tibetan Buddhist practices.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a message shared during a prayer ceremony and posted on social media, the Dalai Lama stated that only his non-profit institution, Gaden Phodrang Foundation of the Dalai Lama, has the legitimate authority to oversee the selection of his reincarnation.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised that the identification of the 15th Dalai Lama should involve consultation with senior leaders of Tibetan Buddhist schools and with spiritual entities known as oath-bound Dharma Protectors, following established historical customs.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama reaffirmed that his reincarnation will occur outside China.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a direct challenge to China, he asserted that the centuries-old spiritual institution bearing his name will endure beyond his death, emphasising that only his inner circle—not Beijing—will have the authority to identify his successor.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has stated that his successor will be born in a free country, suggesting that the next reincarnation could come from the Tibetan diaspora—around 140,000 people worldwide, with about half residing in India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In response, the Chinese government rejected the Dalai Lama's position.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Officials in Beijing stated that the reincarnation of the Dalai Lama, as well as other high-ranking Tibetan Buddhist figures such as the Panchen Lama, must be approved by the central government.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Chinese Foreign Ministry, the government holds ultimate authority in confirming the identity of reincarnated Tibetan spiritual leaders.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Samdhong Rinpoche Lobsang Tenzin, a senior leader of the Dalai Lama's trust, affirmed the continuation of the Dalai Lama institution, stating that both a 15th and 16th Dalai Lama would follow.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said the current Dalai Lama would issue guidelines for identifying his successor.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Deputy speaker of the parliament of the Central Tibetan Administration Dolma Tsering Teykhang accused China of trying to control the reincarnation process and emphasised the need for the Dalai Lama to address the world directly.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his book, *Voice for the Voiceless*, published in 2025, the 14th Dalai Lama said Tibetans worldwide want the institution of the Dalai Lama to continue after his death and specified that his successor would be born in the "free world".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Despite initially advocating for Tibetan independence from 1961 to 1974, the Dalai Lama no longer supports it.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Instead he advocates for more meaningful autonomy for Tibetans within the People's Republic of China.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This approach is known as the "Middle Way".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2005, the 14th Dalai Lama emphasised that Tibet is a part of China, and Tibetan culture and Buddhism are part of Chinese culture.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a speech at Kolkata in 2017, the Dalai Lama stated that Tibetans wanted to stay with China and they did not desire independence.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said that he believed that China after opening up, had changed 40 to 50 per cent of what it was earlier, and that Tibetans wanted to get more development from China.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 2020, the Dalai Lama stated that he did not support Tibetan independence and hoped to visit China as a Nobel Prize winner.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He said "I prefer the concept of a 'republic' in the People's Republic of China.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama maintains close ties with India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2008, the Dalai Lama said that Arunachal Pradesh, partially claimed by China, is part of India, citing the disputed 1914 Simla Accord.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dhundup Gyalpo, the Dalai Lama's eventual secretary in New Delhi, argued that Tibetan and Chinese peoples have no connections apart from a few culinary dishes and that Chinese Buddhists could also be deemed "Indian in spirituality", because both Tibetan and Chinese Buddhism originated from India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has said that, from the perspective of the Buddhist precepts, abortion is an act of killing.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, he clarified a more nuanced position, stating, "... it depends on the circumstances.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If the unborn child will be retarded or if the birth will create serious problems for the parent, these are cases where there can be an exception.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has repeatedly expressed his opposition to the death penalty, saying that it contradicts the Buddhist philosophy of non-violence and that it expresses anger, not compassion.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] During a 2005 visit to Japan, a country which has the death penalty, the Dalai Lama called for the abolition of the death penalty and said in his address, "Criminals, people who commit crimes, usually society rejects these people.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Give them some form of punishment to say they were wrong, but show them they are part of society and can change.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Show them compassion." The Dalai Lama has also praised US states that have abolished the death penalty.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama says that he is active in spreading India's message of nonviolence and religious harmony throughout the world.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] "I am the messenger of India's ancient thoughts the world over." He has said that democracy has deep roots in India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He says he considers India the master and Tibet its disciple, as great scholars went from India to Tibet to teach Buddhism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has noted that millions of people lost their lives in violence and the economies of many countries were ruined due to conflicts in the 20th century.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has also critiqued proselytisation and certain types of conversion, believing the practices to be contrary to the fundamental ideas of religious harmony and spiritual practice.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has stated that "It's very important that our religious traditions live in harmony with one another and I don't think proselytizing contributes to this.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1993, the Dalai Lama attended the World Conference on Human Rights and made a speech titled "Human Rights and Universal Responsibility".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2001, in response to a question from a Seattle schoolgirl, the Dalai Lama said that it is permissible to shoot someone in self-defence (if the person was "trying to kill you") and he emphasised that the shot should not be fatal.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2013, the Dalai Lama criticised Buddhist monks' attacks on Muslims in Myanmar and rejected violence by Buddhists, saying: "Buddha always teaches us about forgiveness, tolerance, compassion.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] If from one corner of your mind, some emotion makes you want to hit, or want to kill, then please remember Buddha's faith. ...
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] All problems must be solved through dialogue, through talk.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has consistently praised India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In December 2018, he said Muslim countries like Bangladesh, Pakistan and Syria should learn about religion from India for peace in the world.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked in 2019 about attacks on the minority community in India including a recent one against a Muslim family in Gurgaon, he said: "There are always a few mischievous people, but that does not mean it a symbol of that nation".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reiterated in December 2021 that he thought India was a role model for religious harmony in the world.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama advocates compassion for animals and frequently urges people to try vegetarianism or at least reduce their consumption of meat.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In Tibet, where historically meat was the most common food, most monks historically have been omnivores, including the Dalai Lamas.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Fourteenth Dalai Lama was raised in a meat-eating family but converted to vegetarianism after arriving in India, where vegetables are much more easily available and vegetarianism is widespread.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He spent many years as a vegetarian, but after contracting hepatitis in India and suffering from weakness, his doctors told him to return to eating meat which he now does twice a week.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This attracted public attention when, during a visit to the White House, he was offered a vegetarian menu but declined by replying, as he is known to do on occasion when dining in the company of non-vegetarians, "I'm a Tibetan monk, not a vegetarian".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His own home kitchen, however, is completely vegetarian.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, the English singer Paul McCartney wrote a letter to the Dalai Lama inquiring why he was not a vegetarian.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] As McCartney later told *The Guardian*, "He wrote back very kindly, saying, 'my doctors tell me that I must eat meat'.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] And I wrote back again, saying, you know, I don't think that's right. [...] I think now he's vegetarian most of the time.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] I think he's now being told, the more he meets doctors from the west, that he can get his protein somewhere else. [...] It just doesn't seem right – the Dalai Lama, on the one hand, saying, 'Hey guys, don't harm sentient beings...
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has referred to himself as a Marxist and has articulated criticisms of capitalism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He reports hearing of communism when he was very young, but only in the context of the destruction of the Mongolian People's Republic.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] It was only when he went on his trip to Beijing that he learned about Marxist theory from his interpreter Baba Phuntsog Wangyal of the Tibetan Communist Party.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At that time, he reports, "I was so attracted to Marxism, I even expressed my wish to become a Communist Party member", citing his favourite concepts of self-sufficiency and equal distribution of wealth.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He does not believe that China implemented "true Marxist policy", and thinks the historical communist states such as the Soviet Union "were far more concerned with their narrow national interests than with the Workers' International".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Moreover, he believes one flaw of historically "Marxist regimes" is that they place too much emphasis on destroying the ruling class, and not enough on compassion.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He finds Marxism superior to capitalism, believing the latter is only concerned with "how to make profits", whereas the former has "moral ethics".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] On India–Pakistan relations, the Dalai Lama in October 2019 said: "There is a difference between Indian and Pakistani Prime Minister's speech at the UN.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Indian Prime Minister talks about peace, and you know what his Pakistan counterpart said, getting China's political support is Pakistan's compulsion.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Pakistani leaders should calm down and think beyond emotions and should follow a realistic approach".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama is outspoken in his concerns about environmental problems, frequently giving public talks on themes related to the environment.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has pointed out that many rivers in Asia originate in Tibet, and that the melting of Himalayan glaciers could affect the countries in which the rivers flow.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He acknowledged official Chinese laws against deforestation in Tibet, but lamented they can be ignored due to possible corruption.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He was quoted as saying "ecology should be part of our daily life"; personally, he takes showers instead of baths, and turns lights off when he leaves a room.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Around 2005, he started campaigning for wildlife conservation, including by issuing a religious ruling against wearing tiger and leopard skins as garments.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama supports the anti-whaling position in the whaling controversy, but has criticised the activities of groups such as the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society (which carries out acts of what it calls aggressive nonviolence against property).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Before the 2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference, he urged national leaders to put aside domestic concerns and take collective action against climate change.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's stances on topics of sexuality have changed over time.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A monk since childhood, the Dalai Lama has said that sex offers fleeting satisfaction and leads to trouble later, while chastity offers a better life and "more independence, more freedom".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has said that problems arising from conjugal life sometimes even lead to suicide or murder.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He has asserted that all religions have the same view about adultery.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also says that in modern times all common, consensual sexual practices that do not cause harm to others are ethically acceptable and that society should accept and respect people who are gay or transgender from a secular point of view.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his 1996 book *Beyond Dogma*, he described a traditional Buddhist definition of an appropriate sexual act as follows: "A sexual act is deemed proper when the couples use the organs intended for sexual intercourse and nothing else ...
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Homosexuality, whether it is between men or between women, is not improper in itself.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] What is improper is the use of organs already defined as inappropriate for sexual contact." He elaborated in 1997, conceding that the basis of that teaching was unknown to him.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He also conveyed his own "willingness to consider the possibility that some of the teachings may be specific to a particular cultural and historic context".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, the Dalai Lama has expressed concern at "reports of violence and discrimination against" LGBT people and urged "respect, tolerance and the full recognition of human rights for all".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2014 interview with Larry King, the Dalai Lama expressed that same-sex marriage is a personal issue, can be ethically socially accepted, and that he personally accepts it.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] However, he also stated that if same-sex marriage is in contradiction with one's chosen traditions, then they should not follow it.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2009, on gender equality and sexism, the Dalai Lama proclaimed at the National Civil Rights Museum in Memphis, Tennessee: "I call myself a feminist.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Isn't that what you call someone who fights for women's rights?" He also said that by nature, women are more compassionate based on their biology and capacity for reproduction and maternal care.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He called on women to "lead and create a more compassionate world", citing the good works of nurses and mothers.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2015 the Dalai Lama said in a BBC interview that if a female were to succeed him, "that female must be attractive, otherwise it is not much use." When asked if he was joking, he replied, "No.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] True!" The Dalai Lama followed with a joke about his success being due to his own appearance.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office later released a statement of apology citing the interaction as a translation error.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a 2020 statement in *Time* magazine on the COVID-19 pandemic, the Dalai Lama said that the pandemic must be combated with compassion, empirical science, prayer, and the courage of healthcare workers.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He emphasised "emotional disarmament" (seeing things with a clear and realistic perspective, without fear or rage) and wrote: "The outbreak of this terrible coronavirus has shown that what happens to one person can soon affect every other being.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In September 2018, speaking at a conference in Malmö, Sweden, the Dalai Lama said "I think Europe belongs to the Europeans", but also that Europe was "morally responsible" for helping "a refugee really facing danger against their life".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He stated that Europe has a responsibility to refugees to "receive them, help them, educate them", but that they should aim to return to their places of origin and that "they ultimately should rebuild their own country".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Speaking to German reporters in 2016, the Dalai Lama said there are "too many" refugees in Europe, adding that "Europe, for example Germany, cannot become an Arab country." He also said that "Germany is Germany".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Dorje Shugden is an entity in Tibetan Buddhism that, since the 1930s, has become a point of contention over whether to include or exclude certain non-Gelug teachings.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1975 publication of the *Yellow Book* containing stories about Dorje Shugden acting wrathfully against Gelugpas who also practised Nyingma, the 14th Dalai Lama, himself a Gelugpa and advocate of an inclusive approach, publicly renounced the practice of Dorje Shugden.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Several groups broke away as a result, notably the New Kadampa Tradition (NKT).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to Tibetologists, the Dalai Lama's disapproval has reduced the prevalence of Shugden sects among Tibetans in China and India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Shugden devotees have since complained about being ostracised when trying to get jobs or receive services.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's supporters expressed that any discrimination is neither systematic nor encouraged by him.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some Shugden movements such as the NKT have organised demonstrations as a form of protest.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some journalists have suggested that the Chinese government has taken advantage of the controversy.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His office said that there was no ban or discrimination against Shugden worshippers.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In October 1998, the Dalai Lama's administration acknowledged that it received $1.7 million a year in the 1960s from the US government through a Central Intelligence Agency program.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] When asked by CIA officer John Kenneth Knaus in 1995 to comment on the CIA Tibetan program, the Dalai Lama replied that though it helped the morale of those resisting the Chinese, "thousands of lives were lost in the resistance" and further, that "the U.S.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Government had involved itself in his country's affairs not to help Tibet but only as a Cold War tactic to challenge the Chinese." As part of the program the Dalai Lama received 180,000 dollars a year from 1959 till 1974 for his own personal use.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] His administration's reception of CIA funding has become one of the grounds for some state-run Chinese newspapers to discredit him along with the Tibetan independence movement.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In his autobiography *Freedom in Exile*, the Dalai Lama criticised the CIA again for supporting the Tibetan independence movement "not because they (the CIA) cared about Tibetan independence, but as part of their worldwide efforts to destabilize all communist governments".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama places highly in global surveys of the world's most admired men, ranking with Pope Francis as among the world's religious leaders cited as the most admired.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama's appeal is variously ascribed to his charismatic personality, international fascination with Buddhism, his universalist values, and international sympathy for the Tibetans.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In the 1990s, many films were released by the American film industry about Tibet, including biopics of the Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] This is attributed to both the Dalai Lama's 1989 Nobel Peace Prize as well as to the euphoria following the Fall of Communism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The most notable films, *Kundun* and *Seven Years in Tibet* (both released in 1997), portrayed "an idyllic pre-1950 Tibet, with a smiling, soft-spoken Dalai Lama at the helm—a Dalai Lama sworn to non-violence": portrayals the Chinese government decried as ahistorical.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has his own pages on Twitter, Facebook and Instagram.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has tried to mobilise international support for Tibetan activities.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has been successful in gaining Western support for himself and the cause of greater Tibetan autonomy, including vocal support from numerous Hollywood celebrities, most notably the actors Richard Gere and Steven Seagal, as well as lawmakers from several major countries.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Photos of the Dalai Lama were banned after March 1959 Lhasa protests until after the end of the Cultural Revolution in 1976.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 1996 the Chinese Communist Party once again reinstated the total prohibition of any photo of the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] According to the Tibet Information Network, "authorities in Tibet have begun banning photographs of the exiled Dalai Lama in monasteries and public places, according to reports from a monitoring group and a Tibetan newspaper.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Plainclothes police went to hotels and restaurants in Lhasa, the Tibetan capital, on 22 and 23 April and ordered Tibetans to remove pictures of the Dalai Lama ..." The ban continues in many locations throughout Tibet today.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In popular media, the Dalai Lama appeared on the HBO late-night talk show *Last Week Tonight with John Oliver* on 5 March 2017, where he discussed issues including Tibetan sovereignty, Tibetan self-immolations, and his succession plans.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] A biographical graphic novel, *Man of Peace*, also envisaging the Dalai Lama's return to Tibet, was published by Tibet House US.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] *The Extraordinary Life of His Holiness the Fourteenth Dalai Lama: An Illuminated Journey,* illustrations and text by artist Rima Fujita, narrated by the Dalai Lama, was published by Simon and Schuster in 2021.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Dalai Lama has received numerous awards and honours worldwide over his spiritual and political career.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] For a more complete list see Awards and honours presented to the 14th Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests and massacre, the Norwegian Nobel Committee awarded him the 1989 Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The Committee officially gave the prize to the Dalai Lama for "the struggle of the liberation of Tibet and the efforts for a peaceful resolution" and "in part a tribute to the memory of Mahatma Gandhi".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2006, he became one of only six people ever to be granted Honorary Citizenship of Canada.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In 2007 he was named Presidential Distinguished Professor at Emory University in Atlanta, Georgia, the first time he accepted a university appointment.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He is the chief Patron of the Maha Bodhi Society of India, conferred upon him at the 2008 Annual General Meeting of the Maha Bodhi Society of India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] At the 68th Annual Grammy Awards, he won the Grammy Award for Best Audio Book, Narration & Storytelling Recording.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In a February 2023 video, the Dalai Lama was seen kissing a boy on the lips and asking the child to suck his tongue.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The incident took place at his temple in Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh, India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Nearly 100 students were in attendance, as well as the boy's mother, a trustee of the event's organiser.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Her son had requested a hug from the Dalai Lama, who then asked for and received a kiss from the child, pulling him closer to touch lips.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] After a pause, the Dalai Lama said "suck my tongue" and, with his tongue out, leaned toward the boy, who appeared nervous and withdrew after sticking out his own tongue.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] In an interview clip released by Voice of Tibet, the boy later said it had been a "good experience" meeting the Dalai Lama, from whom he received a lot of "positive energy".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The interaction was originally recorded by Voice of America, which posted the footage after editing out the "suck my tongue" part.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The removed portion of the clip resurfaced in April 2023, and the Dalai Lama's conduct received negative media coverage.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some victim groups and media commentators raised concerns of "child abuse", while the Tibetan Legal Association warned four Indian news outlets to retract parts of their reporting.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The office of His Holiness issued a statement saying that the Dalai Lama often teases "in an innocent and playful way", adding that he "wishes to apologize to the boy and his family ... for the hurt his words may have caused" and "regrets the incident".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Penpa Tsering, the political leader of the Central Tibetan Administration, called the gesture an "innocent grandfatherly affectionate demeanour" followed by a "jovial prank" with a tongue.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] He and other Tibetans accused "pro-Chinese sources" of being behind the video but have not provided any evidence.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] Some academics, Tibetan leaders and cultural groups described the situation as a cultural misunderstanding.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] They mentioned that sticking out one's tongue is a form of traditional Tibetan greeting to show respect or agreement, stemming from a tradition of performing the gesture to demonstrate that one is not reincarnated from the malevolent king Langdarma, who was said to have a black tongue.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The practice is not known to involve "sucking", however.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/14th-dalai-lama-p03] The controversy also drew attention to past incidents where the Dalai Lama caressed the arm of a disabled girl sitting next to him and touched Lady Gaga's knee through her torn trousers before the star laughed.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The **1959 Tibetan uprising** or **Lhasa uprising** began on 10 March 1959 as a series of protests in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa, fueled by fears that the government of the People's Republic of China planned to arrest the Dalai Lama.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Over the next ten days, the demonstrations evolved from expressions of support for the 14th Dalai Lama to demands for independence and the reversal of the 1951 Chinese annexation of Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] After protesters acquired weapons, China's People's Liberation Army (PLA) shelled protesters in the Dalai Lama's summer palace and deployed tanks to suppress the demonstrations.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Bloody fighting continued for the next three days while the Dalai Lama escaped to India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Thousands of Tibetans were killed during the 1959 uprising, but the exact number is disputed.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The CIA provided extensive support to the uprising, including training for Tibetan fighters, logistical assistance through camps based in Nepal, and the organization of several aerial supply missions.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Earlier in 1956, armed conflict between Tibetan guerrillas and the PLA started in the Kham and Amdo regions, which had been subjected to socialist reform.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Guerrilla warfare later spread to other areas of Tibet and lasted through 1962.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Some regard the Xunhua Incident in 1958 as a precursor of the Tibetan uprising.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The 10 March anniversary of the uprising is observed by exiled Tibetans as Tibetan Uprising Day and Women's Uprising Day.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 19 January 2009, the PRC-controlled legislature in the Tibet Autonomous Region chose 28 March as the national anniversary of Serfs Emancipation Day.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Smith Jr. describes the move as a "counter-propaganda" celebration following the 10 March 2008 unrest in Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] In 1951, the Seventeen Point Agreement between the People's Republic of China (PRC) and representatives of the Dalai Lama was put into effect.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Socialist reforms such as redistribution of land were delayed in Tibet proper.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, eastern Kham and Amdo (western Sichuan / Xikang and Qinghai provinces in the Chinese administrative hierarchy) were outside the administration of the Tibetan government in Lhasa, and were thus treated more like other Chinese provinces, with land redistribution implemented in full.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Khampas and nomads of Amdo traditionally owned their own land.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Armed resistance broke out in Amdo and eastern Kham in June 1956.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Prior to the PLA invasion, relations between Lhasa and the Khampa chieftains had deteriorated, although the Khampa remained spiritually loyal to the Dalai Lama throughout.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Because of these strained relations, the Khampa had actually assisted the Chinese communists in their initial invasion, before becoming the guerrilla resistance they are now known for.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Pandatsang Rapga, a pro-Kuomintang and pro-Republic of China Khampa revolutionary leader, offered the governor of Chamdo, Ngabo Ngawang Jigme, some Khampa fighters in exchange for the Tibetan government recognizing the independence of Kham.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] After the defeat of the Tibetan Army in Chamdo, Rapga started mediating in negotiations between the PRC and the Tibetan rebels.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rapga and Topgay engaged in negotiations with the Chinese during their assault on Chamdo.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Khampas either defected to the Chinese PLA forces or did not fight at all.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Resistance fighters' attacks and People's Liberation Army reprisals against Khampa resistance groups such as the Chushi Gangdruk became increasingly brutal.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Kham's monastic networks came to be used by guerrilla forces to relay messages and hide rebels.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Punitive strikes were carried out by the Chinese government against Tibetan villages and monasteries.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Tibetan exiles assert that threats to bomb the Potala Palace and the Dalai Lama were bluffs made by Chinese military commanders in an attempt to intimidate the guerrilla forces into submission.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa continued to abide by the seventeen-point agreement and sent a delegation to Kham to quell the rebellion.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] After speaking with the rebel leaders, the delegation instead joined the rebellion.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Kham leaders contacted the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), but the CIA under President Dwight D.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Eisenhower insisted it required an official request from Lhasa to support the rebels.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Eventually the CIA began to provide covert support for the rebellion without word from Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] By then the rebellion had spread to Lhasa which had filled with refugees from Amdo and Kham.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Opposition to the Chinese presence in Tibet grew within the city of Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The next day, the Chinese leader saw a report from the PLA General Staff's Operations Department describing rebellions by Tibetans in Sichuan, Yunnan, Gansu, and Qinghai.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] He again stressed that "rebellions like these are extremely favorable for us because they will benefit us in helping to train our troops, train the people, and provide a sufficient reason to crush the rebellion and carry out comprehensive reforms in the future".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The PLA used Hui soldiers, who formerly had served under Ma Bufang to crush the Tibetan revolt in Amdo.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Hui cavalry were stationed in Southern Kham.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The situation in all of Tibet became increasingly tense, as a growing number of Tibetans began to support the Khampa uprising, while "anti-Chinese communist agitation" spread among the Tibetans.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The regional government in Lhasa neither wanted to back a rebellion nor publicly oppose it.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Dissatisfied, the Chinese Communist Party put pressure on the Dalai Lama's government to join the operations against the rebels, and made it increasingly clear that a spread of the insurgency would lead to "all-out repression" in Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] In this unstable situation, the Chinese generals resident in Lhasa was summoned back to mainland China, leaving the inexperienced PLA commander Tan Guansan in charge, just as the date of the Monlam Prayer Festival approached.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] This festival had previously been used by participants to voice "anti-Chinese sentiments".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to historian Tsering Shakya, the Chinese government was pressuring the Dalai Lama to attend the National People's Congress in April 1959, in order to repair China's image in relation to ethnic minorities after the Khampa rebellion.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to the Dalai Lama's memoirs, the invitation came from Chinese General Zhang Jingwu, who proposed that the performance be held at the Chinese military headquarters; the Dalai Lama claimed that he had agreed.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, Tibetologist Sam van Schaik stated that the Dalai Lama was the one who proposed that the dance should take place in the military headquarters as the Norbulingka was too small.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Both parties did not yet agree on a date, and the Dalai Lama seemed to put the event "out of his mind", focusing instead on his ongoing examinations for his Geshe degree as well as the Monlam Prayer Festival.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Besides Tan and the Dalai Lama, nobody was seemingly informed of the plans for the dance.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] As a result, the date for the planned performance was only finalized 5 or 3 days beforehand when Tan reminded the Dalai Lama of the dance; the latter then suggested 10 March.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The decision was seemingly concluded on a whim.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Neither the Kashag nor the Dalai Lama's bodyguards were informed of the Dalai Lama's plans until Chinese officials briefed them on 9 March, one day before the performance was scheduled, and insisted that they would handle the Dalai Lama's security.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Some members of the Kashag were alarmed and concerned that the Dalai Lama might be abducted, recalling a prophecy that told that the Dalai Lama should not exit his palace.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to historian Tsering Shakya, some Tibetan government officials feared that plans were being laid for a Chinese abduction of the Dalai Lama, and spread word to that effect amongst the inhabitants of Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 10 March, several thousand Tibetans surrounded the Dalai Lama's palace to prevent him from leaving or being removed.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The huge crowd had gathered in response to a rumor that the Chinese were planning to arrest the Dalai Lama when he went to a cultural performance at the PLA's headquarters.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] This marked the beginning of the uprising in Lhasa, though Chinese forces had skirmished with guerrillas outside the city in December of the previous year.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The protesters publicly pleaded that the Dalai Lama should not attend the meeting with the Chinese officials, claiming that he would be kidnapped.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Although CCP officials insisted that the "reactionary upper stratum" in Lhasa was responsible for the rumor, there is no way to identify the precise source.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] At first, the violence was directed at Tibetan officials perceived not to have protected the Dalai Lama or to be pro-Chinese; attacks on Chinese started later.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] One of the first casualties of the mob was a senior lama, Pagbalha Soinam Gyamco, who worked with the PRC as a member of the Preparatory Committee of the Tibet Autonomous Region, who was killed and his body dragged by a horse in front of the crowd for 2 kilometres (1.2 mi).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The protesters also began to use openly anti-Chinese slogans such as "The Chinese must go, leave Tibet to Tibetans".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] As protests and violence spread, the Dalai Lama informed the protesters that he would stay at the palace, yet this was no longer enough for the growing crowd.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Protesters began to demand Tibetan independence, and urged the Dalai Lama's government to publicly endorse their actions.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Barricades went up on the streets of Lhasa, and Chinese government soldiers and Tibetan rebel forces began to fortify positions within and around Lhasa in preparation for conflict.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] A petition of support for the armed rebels outside the city was taken up, and an appeal for assistance was made to the Indian consul.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Chinese and Tibetan troops continued moving into position over the next several days, with Chinese artillery pieces being deployed within range of the Dalai Lama's summer palace, the Norbulingka.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 12 March thousands of women gathered in front of the Potala Palace in Lhasa on the ground called Dri-bu-Yul-Khai Thang.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The leader of this nonviolent demonstration was Pamo Kusang.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] This demonstration, now known as Women's Uprising Day, started the Tibetan women's movement for independence.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] After consulting the state oracle and concluding that the situation had become too unstable, the Dalai Lama and his close confidants opted to flee Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 15 March, preparations for the Dalai Lama's evacuation from the city were set in motion, with Tibetan troops being employed to secure an escape route from Lhasa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 17 March, two artillery shells landed near the Dalai Lama's palace, triggering his flight into exile.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Dalai Lama secretly left the palace the following night and slipped out of Lhasa with his family and a small number of officials.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Chinese had not strongly guarded the Potala, as they did not believe it likely that the Dalai Lama would try to flee.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] After reaching Lhoka, the Dalai Lama linked up with Kham rebels who began protecting him and upon reaching Lhotse at the Indian border, he proclaimed the restoration of Tibet's independence.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rumours about the Dalai Lama's disappearance began to spread rapidly on the next day, though most still believed that he was in the palace.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Meanwhile, the situation in the city became increasingly tense, as protesters had seized a number of machine guns.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] At this point, remnants of the Tibetan Army had joined the protesters' ranks.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] On 20 March, the Chinese army responded by shelling the Norbulingka to disperse the crowd, and placed its troops at a barricade that divided the city into a northern and southern part in the following night.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The battle began early on the following day and proved to be "bloody".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Fighting in the streets continued for the next three days.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The last Tibetan resistance was centered on the Jokhang, where Khampa refugees had set up machine guns, while a large number of Tibetans circumambulated the temple in reverence.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The PLA started to attack the Jokhang on 23 March, and a hard-fought, three hours-long battle with many casualties on both sides ensued.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Chinese eventually managed to break through using a tank, whereupon they raised the flag of China on the temple, ending the uprising.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa's streets were reportedly littered with corpses, and at least 4,000 people were arrested.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Two British writers, Stuart and Roma Gelder, visited the Chensel Phodrang palace in the Norbulingka in 1962 and "found its contents meticulously preserved".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Indian government under Nehru expressed concerns of the Tibetan people and condemned China as an aggressive power due to the violent suppression of the revolt by the PLA.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Pandatsang Rapga, a pro-Kuomintang and pro-Republic of China revolutionary Khampa leader, was instrumental in the revolt against the communists.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Kuomintang had a history of using Khampa fighters to oppose both the Dalai Lama's Tibetan government, and battle the Chinese Red Army.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rapga continued to cooperate with the ROC government after it fled to Taiwan.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The ROC government disagreed with the US government on whether Tibet should be independent, since the ROC claimed Tibet as part of its territory.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Rapga agreed to a plan in which the revolt against the communists would include anti feudalism, land reform, a modern government, and to give power to the people.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, the Dalai Lama's first visit to Taiwan in 1997 was said to have somewhat improved the two communities' general relationship, although "tension" allegedly still exists between them due to considerable differences.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Dalai Lama's visit also allowed for Tibetans to visit Taiwan without directly contacting the Mongolian and Tibetan Affairs Commission, and some Tibetans in Taiwan (such as Changa Tsering, an incumbent MTAC committee member) subsequently attended the celebration of the Dalai Lama's visit in 1997.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Tibetan community in Taiwan was also formerly divided between loyalty to the Dalai Lama and Taiwan's MTAC, although the MTAC was formally dissolved in 2017.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The employees and responsibilities of the commission were thus officially reassigned to two places: the Mongolian and Tibetan Cultural Center under the Ministry of Culture, and the expanded Department of Hong Kong, Macao, Inner Mongolia, and Tibet Affairs under the Mainland Affairs Council.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Tibetologist Tom Grunfeld said "the veracity of such a claim is difficult to verify".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Smith, a writer with Radio Free Asia, writes that the "secret documents" came from a 1960 PLA report captured by guerrillas in 1966, with the figures first published by the TGIE in India in 1990.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Smith states that the documents said that 87,000 "enemies were eliminated", but he does not take "eliminated" to mean "killed", as the TGIE does.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Peace Research Institute Oslo (PRIO) estimated 10,000 Tibetan and 2,000 PLA battle deaths.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa had a population of sixty to seventy thousand at the time.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Estimates covering 1956–59 including areas outside Lhasa put civilian deaths at around 60,000 and military deaths at around 40,000.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Following the uprising, the Chinese government launched a wide-reaching campaign to consolidate control and implement socialist reforms across Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Lhasa's three major monasteries - Sera, Ganden, and Drepung were heavily damaged by shelling, with Sera and Drepung reportedly left nearly beyond repair.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to the TGIE, members of the Dalai Lama's bodyguard who were remaining in Lhasa were disarmed and publicly executed, along with Tibetans who were found to be harbouring weapons in their homes.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Thousands of Tibetan monks were executed or arrested, and monasteries and temples around the city were looted or destroyed.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] After the 12 March Women's Uprising demonstration, many of the women who were involved in it were imprisoned, including the leader of the demonstration, Pamo Kusang.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] "Some of them were tortured, died in prison, or were executed." Known as Women's Uprising Day, this demonstration started the Tibetan women's movement for independence.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Meanwhile, the CIA continued to support Tibetan resistance from 1957 to 1972, training agents in the United States and inserting them into Tibet to organize rebellions against the People's Liberation Army (PLA).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] CIA officer Bruce Walker, who oversaw the program, later expressed concern about the hostility that the radio teams encountered from the local population inside Tibet, with at least one group reportedly betrayed by his own brother, and all three agents were arrested.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Despite the arrests, those agents were not mistreated and were later released across the Indian border after undergoing less than a month of propaganda sessions.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] In April 1959, the 19-year-old Panchen Lama, the second ranking spiritual leader in Tibet, residing in Shigatse, called on Tibetans to support the Chinese government.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] However, after a tour through Tibet in May 1962, he wrote a document which is known as the 70,000 Character Petition.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The document was addressed to Zhou Enlai and in it, he criticized Chinese abuses in Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Shortly afterward, he met with Zhou in order to have a discussion about the document.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The outlined petition dealt with the brutal suppression of the Tibetan people both during and after the PLA's invasion of Tibet and the sufferings of the people in The Great Leap Forward.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] In this document, he criticized the suppression that the Chinese authorities had conducted in retaliation for the 1959 Tibetan uprising.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] But in October 1962, the PRC authorities who were dealing with the population criticized the petition.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Chairman Mao called the petition "... a poisoned arrow shot at the Party by reactionary feudal overlords." In 1967, the Panchen Lama was formally arrested and imprisoned until his release in 1977.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] In June 1959, the Buddhist monk Palden Gyatso was arrested for demonstrating during the March uprising by Chinese officials.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] He spent the next 33 years in Chinese prisons and laogai or "reform through labor" camps, the longest term of any Tibetan political prisoner.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] He was tortured, including with a cattle prod that was activated in his mouth and which led to the loss of his teeth.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] As part of the occupation of Tibet, in July 1959, the PLA occupied several Bhutanese enclaves in western Tibet which were under Bhutanese administration for more than 300 years, having been ceded to Bhutan by Ngawang Namgyal in the 17th century.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] These included Darchen, Labrang Monastery, Gartok and several smaller monasteries and villages near Mount Kailas.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Chinese authorities have interpreted the uprising as a revolt by the Tibetan elite against socialist reforms that were improving the lives of Tibetan serfs.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Tibetan exile sources and some independent sources, on the other hand, have usually interpreted it as a popular uprising against Chinese rule.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Historian Tsering Shakya has argued that the revolt reflected widespread dissatisfaction both with the Chinese authorities and also with the Tibetan government in Lhasa, which was seen as unable to protect the Dalai Lama's authority and Tibetan sovereignty.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] The Dalai Lama, fearing for his safety, fled Lhasa on March 17, 1959, and eventually found refuge in India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] Upon reaching India, he and his followers were granted asylum by the Indian government, marking the beginning of his exile.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] From his residence in Dharamshala, Himachal Pradesh, the Dalai Lama played a major role in promoting Tibetan Buddhism internationally and raising awareness of the Tibetan cause.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/1959-tibetan-uprising] According to Chope Paljor Tsering, a former minister in the Central Tibetan Administration, “Buddhism has not only survived, but been revived and appreciated... by many cultures around the world,” suggesting that the Dalai Lama has helped reshape global perceptions of Buddhism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The **3rd Karmapa, Rangjung Dorje** (Tibetan: རང་འབྱུང་རྡོ་རྗེ་, Wylie: rang 'byung rdo rje) (1284–1339) was the 3rd Gyalwa Karmapa and head of the Karma Kagyu school, the largest school within the Kagyu tradition.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He was an important figure in the history of Tibetan Buddhism, who helped to spread Buddha-nature teachings in Tibet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorjé was officially recognized as the first tulku, the reincarnation of Karma Pakshi, in 1282.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The 3rd Karmapa was raised at the Tsurphu Monastery, where he received teachings from both the Kagyu and Nyingma traditions from eminent masters such as Trophu Künden Sherab and Nyenre Gendün Bum.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He became renowned as one of the greatest masters of his time and had a large number of disciples.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He undertook a spiritual retreat on the slopes of Everest, received full ordination, and completed his studies at a significant Kadampa teaching center.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje visited China, where the emperor Toghon Temur became his disciple.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Upon his death, Rangjung Dorje's face is said to have appeared in the moon there.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] As a tulku lineage, the Karmapas were among the earliest recognized Tulkus, reincarnated as deities.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The first Karmapas were influential in the Mongolian Yuan and Chinese Ming courts as well as the Tangut Western Xia Kingdom.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Through visions, he is believed to have received teachings on the "Wheel of Time", the Kalachakra.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] In 1284 he authored an astrological compendium entitled *The Compendium of Astrology* (Tib.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] *rtsis kun bsdus pa*), from which a Tibetan calendar was developed by the lineage of the Gyalwang Karmapas.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Called the Tsurphu tradition calendar or the Tsurluk calendar, his astrological compendium was the basis from which many treatises authored by the subsequent Karmapas and by Jamgon Kongtrul the Great evolved.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The Tsurluk calendar is still used by the Karma Kagyu and overseen by Tsipa Gelek Dhargay, at the 17th Karmapa, Ogyen Trinley Dorje's seat in Rumtek, Sikkim, India.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje was also known as a great practitioner of Traditional Tibetan medicine.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Born to a Nyingma family, Rangjung Dorje was a lineage-holder in both the Karma Kagyu and the Nyingma tradition of Dzogchen.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He was a disciple of the Nyingma master Rigdzin Kumaradza Shönnu Gyelpo (Tibetan: rig 'dzin ku ma ra dza gzhon nu rgyal po; 1266–1343) who passed on to him the "heart-essence" (nying-thig) teachings transmitted by Padmasambhava and Vimalamitra (the Khandro Nyingtik and Vima Nyingtik respectively).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] He also encountered the Nyingma master Longchenpa, who transmitted to him certain Dzogchen teachings.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] In exchange, Rangjung Dorje imparted important "New Translation" Tantras to Longchenpa.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje was also a "Treasure revealer" of termas.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] The Karma Kagyu Dzogchen transmission that arose from his lineage is known as the "Karma-Nyingthig" (Tibetan: kar ma snying thig; Essence of the Heart of the Karma School).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] In 1321 the famous scholar Dolpopa (1292–1361) visited Tsurphu Monastery for the first time and had extensive discussions with Rangjung Dorje about doctrinal issues.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] It appears that Rangjung Dorje almost certainly influenced the development of some of Dolpopa's theories, possibly including his Zhentong (*gzhan stong*) method.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] According to Karma phrin las, *Dri lan yid*, 91-92, his teacher, Chödrak Gyatso, the Seventh Karmapa, interpreted the nature of Zhentong (*gzhan stong*) accepted by Rangjung Dorje.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] 15) conveys that the Third Karmapa was a systematizer of the Chöd developed by Machig Labdrön and lists a number of his works on Chod consisting of redactions, outlines and commentaries.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Yungtön Dorjepel (1284–1365), (the previous incarnation of the First Panchen Lama, Khedrup Je), studied the Great Perfection due to the great inspiration of Rangjung Dorje.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/3rd-karmapa-rangjung-dorje] Rangjung Dorje was a noted scholar who composed many significant texts, the most famous of which is the *Profound Inner Meaning* (Wylie: *zab mo nang don*), which concern the Vajrayana inner yoga practices.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] The **969 Movement** (Burmese: ၉၆၉ လှုပ်ရှားမှု) is a Buddhist nationalist organisation opposed to the perceived expansion of Islam in predominantly Buddhist Myanmar.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] The three digits of 969 "symbolise the virtues of the Buddha, Buddhist practices and the Buddhist community".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] The first 9 represents the nine special attributes of the Buddha in Buddhism, the 6 represents the six special attributes of his teachings (the Dharma), and the second 9 represents the nine special attributes of the Sangha (the Buddhist monastic community).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Those special attributes are the Three Jewels of the Buddha.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] In the past, the Buddha, Sangha, Dharma, the wheel of Dharma, and "969" were Buddhist signs.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] The movement has had strong reactions within and beyond Myanmar.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] It has received criticism in international media.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] In April 2013, *The Straits Times* reported that critics remained sceptical after Wirathu, the movement's leader, responded to recent anti-Muslim violence with pledges to work for peace.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Various media organizations have described the movement as being anti-Muslim or "Islamophobic".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] The movement's Myanmar Buddhist supporters deny it is anti-Muslim, with Wirathu stating it is a protective movement about targeting "Bengalis who are terrorizing ethnic Rakhine (Buddhists)".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Alex Bookbinder, in *The Atlantic*, links the movement's origins in a book written in the late 1990s by Kyaw Lwin, a functionary in the Ministry of Religious Affairs, and its precepts are rooted in a traditional belief in numerology.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Across South Asia, Muslims represent the phrase "In the Name of God, the Compassionate and Merciful" with the number 786, and businesses display the number to indicate that they are Muslim-owned.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] 969 proponents see this as a Muslim plot to conquer Burma in the 21st century, based on the premise that 7 plus 8 plus 6 is equal to 21.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] The number 969 is intended to be 786's cosmological opposite.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Wirathu is regarded as the movement's highest protector.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] It has been reported that he advocates the boycott of shops owned by Muslims.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Wirathu has himself stated that the movement has been treated as a scapegoat by being unfairly blamed for events like the 2012 Rakhine State riots, and maintains that "969 is not violent".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] The *Asia Times Online* has described him as a "complex figure" who demonises Muslims, but also protests police violence.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] An article in *The Straits Times* says a source indicated that Wirathu had changed his tone and "pledged to promote peace among religious communities".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] The cover story of the 20 June 2013 issue of *Time* magazine called Wirathu "The Face of Buddhist Terror".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] "You can be full of kindness and love, but you cannot sleep next to a mad dog", Wirathu said, referring to Muslims.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] "If we are weak", he said, "our land will become Muslim".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] "Some people misunderstood the title [of the *Time* article] ... seeing it as an insult to religion", said Dr.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] "They believe it’s equating Buddhism with terrorism".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] After the publication of the *Time* article, Wirathu denied responsibility for anti-Muslim violence.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Shortly after, the June 2013 issue of *Time* featuring Wirathu was banned in Myanmar.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Burma's government has objected to the magazine article.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Authorities deny they are defending the monk, Wirathu, but said they were concerned the article could create problems after recent unrest between Buddhists and Muslims.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Burmese President Thein Sein, however, has defended Wirathu, saying the monk's order was striving for peace and prosperity and that the report undermined efforts to rebuild trust between faiths.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] "The government is currently striving with religious leaders, political parties, media and the people to rid Myanmar [Burma] of unwanted conflicts," he added.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Wirathu has said that the *Time* article was not against Buddhism, just against him.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] In an interview with *The Irrawaddy* magazine, he also alleged Muslim extremists were behind the article and planning to wage jihad against Burma.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Hundreds of protesters took to the streets of Yangon early in the afternoon on 30 June 2013 in a peaceful demonstration against *Time* magazine's article on Wirathu and the 969 movement.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Marching monks held a banner proclaiming that Wirathu is "not a terrorist, but a protector of race, language and religion".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Speaking to Mizzima News, one demonstrator, a 51-year-old office manager, said, "Time magazine is wrong.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] In September 2014, Wirathu attended a "Great Sangha Conference" in Colombo organised by Bodu Bala Sena.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Wirathu said that his 969 Movement would work with the Bodu Bala Sena.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] The movement is seeking to draft a law that would forbid Buddhist women from marrying non-Buddhist men without the permission of local officials.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Dhammapiya, a senior monk who helped write the original proposal for the laws, said they were meant to encourage peace between different faiths and to "protect" Buddhist women from being forced to convert to Islam when they married Muslim men.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/969-movement] Government religious regulatory authorities, while supporting the protection of the Buddhist faith from perceived Islamic threats, reject the legal initiatives of the 969 movement and "prohibited the creation of formal organisations" based on 969 principles.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The earliest surviving written accounts of Buddhism are the Edicts written by King Ashoka, a well-known Buddhist king who propagated Buddhism throughout Asia, and is honored by both Theravada and Mahayana schools of Buddhism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The authority of the Edicts of Ashoka as a historical record is suggested by the mention of numerous topics omitted as well as corroboration of numerous accounts found in the Theravada and Mahayana Tripitakas written down centuries later.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] 257 BCE, mentions the prohibition of animal sacrifices in Ashoka's Maurya Empire as well as his commitment to vegetarianism; however, whether the Sangha was vegetarian in part or in whole is unclear from these edicts.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] There is a divergence of views within Buddhism as to whether vegetarianism is required; with some schools of Buddhism rejecting such a requirement.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Some Buddhists avoid meat consumption because of the first precept in Buddhism: "I undertake the precept to refrain from taking life".
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Other Buddhists disagree with this conclusion.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Many Buddhist vegetarians also oppose meat-eating based on scriptural injunctions against flesh-eating recorded in Mahayana sutras.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The most clear reference in Theravada Buddhism to monastic consumption of non-vegetarian food is found in the Pali Canon, where the Buddha once explicitly refused a suggestion by Devadatta to mandate vegetarianism in the monks' Vinaya monastic code.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] This refusal to proscribe non-vegetarian food is within the context of Buddhist monastics receiving alms food.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The Buddha in the Aṅguttara Nikāya 3.38 *Sukhamala Sutta*, before his enlightenment, describes his family being wealthy enough to provide non-vegetarian meals even to his servants.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] After becoming enlightened, he respectfully accepted any kind of alms food offered with good intention, including meat (within the limitations described above), fruits and vegetables.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In the same text, a former Jaina converted into Buddhism, Siha, gives alms including meat to the Buddha and his monks, ordering one of his servants to buy fresh meat from the market.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Other Jain ascetics comment unfavorably, accusing Siha of killing an animal explicitly for the consumption of the Buddha, but Siha denies such a thing.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Also in the *Jivaka Sutta*, Buddha instructs a monk or nun to accept, without any discrimination, whatever alms food is offered with good will, including meat.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] But this is not, strictly speaking, a dietary rule because the Buddha, on one particular occasion, specifically refused suggestions by Devadatta to institute vegetarianism in the Sangha.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In the *Amagandha Sutta* in the Sutta Nipata, a vegetarian Brahmin confronts Kassapa Buddha (a previous Buddha before Gautama Buddha) in regard to the evils of eating meat.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The Brahmin insisted his higher status is well-deserved due to his observance of a vegetarian diet.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The Buddha countered the argument by listing acts which cause real moral defilement (i.e. those acts in opposition to Buddhist ethics) and then stating the mere consumption of meat is not equivalent to those acts.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] There were monastic guidelines prohibiting consumption of 10 types of meat: that of humans, elephants, horses, dogs, snakes, lions, tigers, leopards, bears and hyenas.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] This is because these animals (allegedly) can be provoked by the smell of the flesh of their own kind, or because eating of such flesh would generate a bad reputation for the Sangha.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Paul Breiter, a student of Ajahn Chah, states that some bhikkhus in the Thai Forest Tradition choose to be vegetarian and that Ajahn Sumedho encouraged supporters to prepare vegetarian food for the temple.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] There are a significant minority of Theravadin laypersons who practice vegetarianism especially in Thailand and Sri Lanka.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Mahayana views on vegetarianism are within the broader framework of Buddhist ethics or Śīla.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The aim of Buddhist vegetarianism is to give rise to compassion and the upholder of vegetarianism is expected to (at least faithfully attempt to) observe Buddhist ethics.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The Buddhist vegetarian who does not observe Buddhist ethics is not seen as a true Buddhist vegetarian.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] According to the *Mahāyāna Mahāparinirvāṇa Sūtra*, a Mahayana sutra giving Gautama Buddha's final teachings, the Buddha insisted that his followers should not eat any kind of meat or fish.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Even vegetarian food that has been touched by meat should be washed before being eaten.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Also, it is not permissible for the monk or nun just to pick out the non-meat portions of a diet – the whole meal must be rejected.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Moreover, according to the Buddha in the *Aṅgulimālīya Sūtra*, since all beings share the same "Dhatu" (spiritual Principle or Essence) and are intimately related to one another, killing and eating other sentient creatures is tantamount to a form of self-killing and cannibalism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The sutras which inveigh against meat-eating include the *Mahāyāna Mahāparinirvāṇa Sūtra*, the *Śūraṅgama Sūtra*, the *Brahmajāla Sūtra*, the *Aṅgulimālīya Sūtra*, the *Mahamegha Sutra*, and the *Laṅkāvatāra Sūtra*.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] He specifically rejects the idea that monks who go out begging and receive meat from a donor should eat it: "[I]t should be rejected...
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] I say that even meat, fish, game, dried hooves and scraps of meat left over by others constitutes an infraction...
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] I teach the harm arising from meat-eating." The Buddha also predicts in this sutra that later monks will "hold spurious writings to be the authentic Dharma" and will concoct their own sutras and falsely claim that the Buddha allows the eating of meat, whereas he says he does not.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] This passage has been seen as questionable by a small minority of Mahayana Buddhist writers (eg.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In several other Mahayana scriptures, too (e.g., the Mahayana jataka tales), the Buddha is seen clearly to indicate that meat-eating is undesirable and karmically unwholesome.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Some suggest that the rise of monasteries in Mahayana tradition to be a contributing factor in the emphasis on vegetarianism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In the monastery, food was prepared specifically for monastics.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In this context, large quantities of meat would have been specifically prepared (killed) for them.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Henceforth, when monastics from the Indian geographical sphere of influence migrated to China from the year 65 CE on, they met followers who provided them with money instead of food.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] From those days onwards, Chinese monastics, and others who came to inhabit northern countries, cultivated their own vegetable plots and bought food in the market.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] This remains the dominant practice in China, Vietnam, and most Korean Mahayana temples; the exceptions being some Korean Mahayana temples who traced their lineages back to Japan.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Mahayana lay Buddhists often eat vegetarian diets on the vegetarian dates *Zhai qi* (Chinese: 齋期; pinyin: *Zhāi qí*).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] There are different arrangement of the dates, from several days to three months in each year, in some traditions, the celebration of the bodhisattva Avalokiteśvara's birthday, Bodhi Day and Great Renunciation days hold the highest importance to be vegetarian.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Some Vajrayana practitioners both drink alcohol and eat meat.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Many traditions of the Ganachakra which is a type of Panchamakara puja prescribed the offering and ingestion of meat and alcohol, although this practice is now often only a symbolic one, with no actual meat or alcohol ingested.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The 14th Dalai Lama and other esteemed lamas invite their audiences to adopt vegetarianism when they can.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] When asked in recent years what he thinks of vegetarianism, the 14th Dalai Lama has said: "It is wonderful.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] We must absolutely promote vegetarianism." The Dalai Lama tried becoming a vegetarian and promoted vegetarianism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In 1999, it was published that the Dalai Lama would only be vegetarian every other day and partakes of meat regularly.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] When he is in Dharamsala, he is vegetarian, but not necessarily when he is outside Dharamsala.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Tenzin Wangyal Rinpoche became vegetarian in 2008.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Arjia Rinpoche became vegetarian in 1999.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In the modern world, attitudes toward vegetarianism vary by location.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In Sri Lanka and the Theravada countries of South East Asia, monks are obliged by the monastic code, Vinaya to accept almost any food that is offered to them, including meat, unless they suspect the meat was slaughtered specifically for them.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Theravadin monks are also not supposed to choose or request for any specific food during their pindapata (alms collection).
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Pure Vegetarianism or Veganism is Indic in origin and is still practiced in India by some adherents of Dharmic religions such as Jainism and in the case of Hinduism, lacto-vegetarianism with the additional abstention of pungent or fetid vegetables.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] A minority of Buddhist lay believers are year-long or life-long vegetarians.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Many lay followers typically adhere to monastic-style vegetarianism on Lunar New Year Eve, commemorative holidays and ancestral feast days, as well as the first and fifteenth days of each month on the lunar calendar.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Some lay followers also follow monastic-style vegetarianism on the six-day (Chinese: 六日齋; pinyin: *Liù rì zhāi*), ten-day (Chinese: 十日齋; pinyin: *Shí rì zhāi*), Guan-yin (Avalokiteśvara) vegetarian (Chinese: 觀音齋; pinyin: *Guānyīn zhāi*) etc., and follow according to that lunar calendar schedule.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Other Buddhist lay-followers also follow less stringent forms of vegetarianism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Most Buddhist lay-followers however are not vegetarians.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Some Zhaijiao lay adherents also do not eat any meat.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Japan initially received Chinese Buddhism in the 6th century.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In 675, Emperor Tenmu issued an edict prohibiting eating the meat of cows, horses, dogs, monkeys, and roosters, as recorded in the Nihon Shoki.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Tenmu was a strong proponent of Buddhism, and these views were bolstered by Shinto perspectives that reviewed blood and dead bodies as impure (Japanese: 穢れ *kegare*) and to be avoided.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Despite this, animal products remained in the Japanese diet long after the 675 edict.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] References to hunting and eating deer and wild boar continued throughout the ancient and medieval period into the 16th century as an occasional part of the diet for all but those in the poorer agrarian classes.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The court nobles also ate red meat occasionally, despite being obliged to follow Buddhist principles closely, although it was viewed as inferior to eating fish and birds.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Around the 9th century, two Japanese monks (Kūkai and Saichō), introduced Vajrayana Buddhism into Japan, and this soon became the dominant Buddhism among the nobility.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In particular, Saichō, who founded the Tendai sect of Japanese Buddhism, reduced the number of vinaya code to 66.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] (円戒 yuán jiè) During the 12th century, a number of monks from Tendai sects founded new schools (Zen, Pure Land Buddhism) and de-emphasised vegetarianism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Nichiren Buddhism today likewise deemphasises vegetarianism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Zen does tend generally to look favourably upon vegetarianism.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Shingon Buddhism, founded by Kūkai, recommends vegetarianism and requires it at certain times, but it is not always strictly required for monks and nuns.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Buddhist vegetarianism (aka Shojin Ryori), also dictates Kinkunshoku (禁葷食) which is to not use meat as well as Gokun (五葷 5 vegetables from the allium family) in their cooking.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In 1872 of the Meiji restoration, as part of the opening up of Japan to Western influence, Emperor Meiji lifted the ban on the consumption of red meat.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The removal of the ban encountered resistance and in one notable response, ten monks attempted to break into the Imperial Palace.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The monks asserted that due to foreign influence, large numbers of Japanese had begun eating meat and that this was "destroying the soul of the Japanese people." Several of the monks were killed during the break-in attempt, and the remainder were arrested.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The practice of non-harming forms the basis of all three vehicles of Buddhist philosophy.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] The Buddha made clear distinctions between eating meat and killing, by giving instructions on the three-fold purity of meat.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] In Tibet, where vegetables are scarce, meat is often consumed as a form of sustenance.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] However, records show that in Tibet, the practice of vegetarianism was encouraged as early as the 14th and 15th centuries by renowned Buddhist teachers such as Chödrak Gyatso and Mikyö Dorje, 8th Karmapa Lama.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Contemporary Buddhist teachers such as the Dalai Lama, and The 17th Karmapa Ogyen Trinley Dorje, invite their audiences to adopt vegetarianism whenever they can.
[src:buddhist-vegetarianism/buddhist-vegetarianism] Chatral Rinpoche in particular stated that anyone who wished to be his student must be vegetarian.
